SpaceCenter.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Provides functionality to interact with Kerbal Space Program. This includes controlling
the active vessel, managing its resources, planning maneuver nodes and auto-piloting.
</summary>
</doc>

LaunchableVessels.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Returns a list of vessels from the given <paramref name="craftDirectory" /> that can be launched.
</summary>
  <param name="craftDirectory">Name of the directory in the current saves "Ships" directory. For example <c>"VAB"</c> or <c>"SPH"</c>.</param>
</doc>

LaunchVessel.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Launch a vessel.
</summary>
  <param name="craftDirectory">Name of the directory in the current saves "Ships" directory, that contains the craft file. For example <c>"VAB"</c> or <c>"SPH"</c>.</param>
  <param name="name">Name of the vessel to launch. This is the name of the ".craft" file in the save directory, without the ".craft" file extension.</param>
  <param name="launchSite">Name of the launch site. For example <c>"LaunchPad"</c> or <c>"Runway"</c>.</param>
</doc>

LaunchVesselFromVAB.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Launch a new vessel from the VAB onto the launchpad.
</summary>
  <param name="name">Name of the vessel to launch.</param>
  <remarks>
This is equivalent to calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.LaunchVessel" /> with the craft directory set to "VAB" and the launch site set to "LaunchPad".
</remarks>
</doc>

LaunchVesselFromSPH.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Launch a new vessel from the SPH onto the runway.
</summary>
  <param name="name">Name of the vessel to launch.</param>
  <remarks>
This is equivalent to calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.LaunchVessel" /> with the craft directory set to "SPH" and the launch site set to "Runway".
</remarks>
</doc>

CanRailsWarpAt.documentation: Returns true if regular "on-rails" time warp can be used, at the specified warp . The maximum time warp rate is limited by various things, including how close the active vessel is to a planet. See the KSP wiki for details. The warp factor to check.

WarpTo.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Uses time acceleration to warp forward to a time in the future, specified
by universal time <paramref name="ut" />. This call blocks until the desired
time is reached. Uses regular "on-rails" or physical time warp as appropriate.
For example, physical time warp is used when the active vessel is traveling
through an atmosphere. When using regular "on-rails" time warp, the warp
rate is limited by <paramref name="maxRailsRate" />, and when using physical
time warp, the warp rate is limited by <paramref name="maxPhysicsRate" />.
</summary>
  <param name="ut">The universal time to warp to, in seconds.</param>
  <param name="maxRailsRate">The maximum warp rate in regular "on-rails" time warp.</param>
  <param name="maxPhysicsRate">The maximum warp rate in physical time warp.</param>
  <returns>When the time warp is complete.</returns>
</doc>

TransformPosition.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Converts a position vector from one reference frame to another.
</summary>
  <param name="position">Position vector in reference frame <paramref name="from" />.</param>
  <param name="from">The reference frame that the position vector is in.</param>
  <param name="to">The reference frame to covert the position vector to.</param>
  <returns>The corresponding position vector in reference frame <paramref name="to" />.</returns>
</doc>

TransformDirection.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Converts a direction vector from one reference frame to another.
</summary>
  <param name="direction">Direction vector in reference frame <paramref name="from" />.</param>
  <param name="from">The reference frame that the direction vector is in.</param>
  <param name="to">The reference frame to covert the direction vector to.</param>
  <returns>The corresponding direction vector in reference frame <paramref name="to" />.</returns>
</doc>

TransformRotation.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Converts a rotation from one reference frame to another.
</summary>
  <param name="rotation">Rotation in reference frame <paramref name="from" />.</param>
  <param name="from">The reference frame that the rotation is in.</param>
  <param name="to">The corresponding rotation in reference frame <paramref name="to" />.</param>
  <returns>The corresponding rotation in reference frame <paramref name="to" />.</returns>
</doc>

TransformVelocity.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Converts a velocity vector (acting at the specified position vector) from one
reference frame to another. The position vector is required to take the
relative angular velocity of the reference frames into account.
</summary>
  <param name="position">Position vector in reference frame <paramref name="from" />.</param>
  <param name="velocity">Velocity vector in reference frame <paramref name="from" />.</param>
  <param name="from">The reference frame that the position and velocity vectors are in.</param>
  <param name="to">The reference frame to covert the velocity vector to.</param>
  <returns>The corresponding velocity in reference frame <paramref name="to" />.</returns>
</doc>

get_WarpMode.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The current time warp mode. Returns <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.WarpMode.None" /> if time
warp is not active, <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.WarpMode.Rails" /> if regular "on-rails" time warp
is active, or <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.WarpMode.Physics" /> if physical time warp is active.
</summary>
</doc>

get_WarpRate.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The current warp rate. This is the rate at which time is passing for
either on-rails or physical time warp. For example, a value of 10 means
time is passing 10x faster than normal. Returns 1 if time warp is not
active.
</summary>
</doc>

get_WarpFactor.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The current warp factor. This is the index of the rate at which time
is passing for either regular "on-rails" or physical time warp. Returns 0
if time warp is not active. When in on-rails time warp, this is equal to
<see cref="M:SpaceCenter.RailsWarpFactor" />, and in physics time warp, this is equal to
<see cref="M:SpaceCenter.PhysicsWarpFactor" />.
</summary>
</doc>

get_RailsWarpFactor.documentation: The time warp rate, using regular "on-rails" time warp. A value between 0 and 7 inclusive. 0 means no time warp. Returns 0 if physical time warp is active. If requested time warp factor cannot be set, it will be set to the next lowest possible value. For example, if the vessel is too close to a planet. See the KSP wiki for details.

set_RailsWarpFactor.documentation: The time warp rate, using regular "on-rails" time warp. A value between 0 and 7 inclusive. 0 means no time warp. Returns 0 if physical time warp is active. If requested time warp factor cannot be set, it will be set to the next lowest possible value. For example, if the vessel is too close to a planet. See the KSP wiki for details.

get_PhysicsWarpFactor.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The physical time warp rate. A value between 0 and 3 inclusive. 0 means
no time warp. Returns 0 if regular "on-rails" time warp is active.
</summary>
</doc>

set_PhysicsWarpFactor.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The physical time warp rate. A value between 0 and 3 inclusive. 0 means
no time warp. Returns 0 if regular "on-rails" time warp is active.
</summary>
</doc>

get_MaximumRailsWarpFactor.documentation: The current maximum regular "on-rails" warp factor that can be set. A value between 0 and 7 inclusive. See the KSP wiki for details.

AutoPilot_get_Error.documentation:

has not been engaged and SAS is not enabled or is in stability assist mode.

<doc>

Returns zero if the auto-pilot has not been engaged or no target roll is set.

AutoPilot_get_StoppingTime.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The maximum amount of time that the vessel should need to come to a complete stop.
This determines the maximum angular velocity of the vessel.
A vector of three stopping times, in seconds, one for each of the pitch, roll and yaw axes.
Defaults to 0.5 seconds for each axis.
</summary>
</doc>

AutoPilot_set_StoppingTime.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The maximum amount of time that the vessel should need to come to a complete stop.
This determines the maximum angular velocity of the vessel.
A vector of three stopping times, in seconds, one for each of the pitch, roll and yaw axes.
Defaults to 0.5 seconds for each axis.
</summary>
</doc>

AutoPilot_get_DecelerationTime.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The time the vessel should take to come to a stop pointing in the target direction.
This determines the angular acceleration used to decelerate the vessel.

Defaults to 5 seconds for each axis.
</summary>
</doc>

</summary>
</doc>

<doc>
  <summary>
The angle at which the autopilot considers the vessel to be pointing close to the target.
This determines the midpoint of the target velocity attenuation function.

Defaults to 1° for each axis.
</summary>
</doc>

vessels moment of inertia and available torque. Defaults to <c>true</c>.
See <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.AutoPilot.TimeToPeak" /> and  <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.AutoPilot.Overshoot" />.

<list type="bullet"><item><description>The origin is at the center of the body.

</description></item><item><description>The y-axis points in the orbital prograde direction.
</description></item><item><description>The z-axis points in the orbital normal direction.
</description></item></list></summary>

</doc>

Measured from the center of mass of the vessel.
</summary>
</doc>

<doc>

The elevation of the terrain under the vessel, in meters. This is the height of the terrain above sea level,
and is negative when the vessel is over the sea.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_Latitude.documentation: The latitude of the vessel for the body being orbited, in degrees.

Flight_get_Longitude.documentation: The longitude of the vessel for the body being orbited, in degrees.

Flight_get_Velocity.documentation:

Flight_get_Speed.documentation:
<doc>

The speed of the vessel in meters per second.
</summary>

<doc>

The horizontal speed of the vessel in meters per second.

</doc>

Flight_get_VerticalSpeed.documentation:

</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_CenterOfMass.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The position of the center of mass of the vessel.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_Direction.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The direction vector that the vessel is pointing in.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_Pitch.documentation:

The pitch angle of the vessel relative to the horizon, in degrees. A value between -90° and +90°.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_Heading.documentation:

The heading angle of the vessel relative to north, in degrees. A value between 0° and 360°.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_Roll.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The roll angle of the vessel relative to the horizon, in degrees. A value between -180° and +180°.
</summary>
</doc>

The unit direction vector pointing in the prograde direction.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_Retrograde.documentation:
<doc>

The unit direction vector pointing in the retrograde direction.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_Normal.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>

</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_AntiNormal.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The unit direction vector pointing in the anti-normal direction.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_Radial.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The unit direction vector pointing in the radial direction.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_AntiRadial.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The unit direction vector pointing in the anti-radial direction.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_AtmosphereDensity.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The current density of the atmosphere around the vessel, in <math>kg/m^3</math>.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_DynamicPressure.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The dynamic pressure acting on the vessel, in Pascals. This is a measure of the strength of the
aerodynamic forces. It is equal to <math>\frac{1}{2} . \mbox{air density} .  \mbox{velocity}^2</math>.
It is commonly denoted <math>Q</math>.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_StaticPressureAtMSL.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The static atmospheric pressure at mean sea level, in Pascals.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_StaticPressure.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The static atmospheric pressure acting on the vessel, in Pascals.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_AerodynamicForce.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The total aerodynamic forces acting on the vessel, as a vector pointing in the direction of the force, with its
magnitude equal to the strength of the force in Newtons.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_Lift.documentation: The aerodynamic lift currently acting on the vessel, as a vector pointing in the direction of the force, with its magnitude equal to the strength of the force in Newtons.

Flight_get_Drag.documentation: The aerodynamic drag currently acting on the vessel, as a vector pointing in the direction of the force, with its magnitude equal to the strength of the force in Newtons.

Flight_get_SpeedOfSound.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The speed of sound, in the atmosphere around the vessel, in <math>m/s</math>.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_Mach.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The speed of the vessel, in multiples of the speed of sound.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_ReynoldsNumber.documentation: The vessels Reynolds number. Requires Ferram Aerospace Research.

Flight_get_TrueAirSpeed.documentation: The true air speed of the vessel, in m/s.

Flight_get_EquivalentAirSpeed.documentation: The equivalent air speed of the vessel, in m/s.

Flight_get_TerminalVelocity.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
An estimate of the current terminal velocity of the vessel, in <math>m/s</math>.
This is the speed at which the drag forces cancel out the force of gravity.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_AngleOfAttack.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Gets the pitch angle between the orientation of the vessel and its velocity vector, in degrees.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_SideslipAngle.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Gets the yaw angle between the orientation of the vessel and its velocity vector, in degrees.
</summary>
</doc>

Flight_get_TotalAirTemperature.documentation: The total air temperature of the atmosphere around the vessel, in Kelvin. This temperature includes the and the vessel's kinetic energy.

Flight_get_StaticAirTemperature.documentation: The static (ambient) temperature of the atmosphere around the vessel, in Kelvin.

Flight_get_StallFraction.documentation: Gets the current amount of stall, between 0 and 1. A value greater than 0.005 indicates a minor stall and a value greater than 0.5 indicates a large-scale stall. Requires Ferram Aerospace Research.

Flight_get_DragCoefficient.documentation: Gets the coefficient of drag. This is the amount of drag produced by the vessel. It depends on air speed, air density and wing area. Requires Ferram Aerospace Research.

Flight_get_LiftCoefficient.documentation: Gets the coefficient of lift. This is the amount of lift produced by the vessel, and depends on air speed, air density and wing area. Requires Ferram Aerospace Research.

Flight_get_BallisticCoefficient.documentation: Gets the ballistic coefficient. Requires Ferram Aerospace Research.

Flight_get_ThrustSpecificFuelConsumption.documentation: Gets the thrust specific fuel consumption for the jet engines on the vessel. This is a measure of the efficiency of the engines, with a lower value indicating a more efficient vessel. This value is the number of Newtons of fuel that are burned, per hour, to produce one newton of thrust. Requires Ferram Aerospace Research.

<doc>

</summary>

</remarks>

of mass of the object in orbit, and the center of mass of the body around which it is orbiting.
</summary>

</remarks>
</doc>

Orbit_get_Speed.documentation:
<doc>

</summary>

Orbit_get_TimeToPeriapsis.documentation:

<doc>

Whether the docking port has a shield.
</summary>
</doc>

DockingPort_get_Shielded.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The state of the docking ports shield, if it has one.

Returns <c>true</c> if the docking port has a shield, and the shield is
closed. Otherwise returns <c>false</c>. When set to <c>true</c>, the shield is
closed, and when set to <c>false</c> the shield is opened. If the docking
port does not have a shield, setting this attribute has no effect.
</summary>
</doc>

DockingPort_set_Shielded.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The state of the docking ports shield, if it has one.

Returns <c>true</c> if the docking port has a shield, and the shield is
closed. Otherwise returns <c>false</c>. When set to <c>true</c>, the shield is
closed, and when set to <c>false</c> the shield is opened. If the docking
port does not have a shield, setting this attribute has no effect.
</summary>
</doc>

DockingPort_get_ReferenceFrame.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The reference frame that is fixed relative to this docking port, and
oriented with the port.
<list type="bullet"><item><description>The origin is at the position of the docking port.</description></item><item><description>The axes rotate with the docking port.</description></item><item><description>The x-axis points out to the right side of the docking port.</description></item><item><description>The y-axis points in the direction the docking port is facing.</description></item><item><description>The z-axis points out of the bottom off the docking port.</description></item></list></summary>
  <remarks>
This reference frame is not necessarily equivalent to the reference frame
for the part, returned by <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.ReferenceFrame" />.
</remarks>
</doc>

Engine_get_Part.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The part object for this engine.
</summary>

Engine_get_Active.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Whether the engine is active. Setting this attribute may have no effect,
depending on <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Engine.CanShutdown" /> and <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Engine.CanRestart" />.
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_set_Active.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Whether the engine is active. Setting this attribute may have no effect,
depending on <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Engine.CanShutdown" /> and <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Engine.CanRestart" />.
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_Thrust.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The current amount of thrust being produced by the engine, in Newtons.
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_AvailableThrust.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The amount of thrust, in Newtons, that would be produced by the engine
when activated and with its throttle set to 100%.
Returns zero if the engine does not have any fuel.
Takes the engine's current <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Engine.ThrustLimit" /> and atmospheric conditions into account.
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_MaxThrust.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The amount of thrust, in Newtons, that would be produced by the engine
when activated and fueled, with its throttle and throttle limiter set to 100%.
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_MaxVacuumThrust.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The maximum amount of thrust that can be produced by the engine in a
vacuum, in Newtons. This is the amount of thrust produced by the engine
when activated, <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Engine.ThrustLimit" /> is set to 100%, the main
vessel's throttle is set to 100% and the engine is in a vacuum.
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_ThrustLimit.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The thrust limiter of the engine. A value between 0 and 1. Setting this
attribute may have no effect, for example the thrust limit for a solid
rocket booster cannot be changed in flight.
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_set_ThrustLimit.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The thrust limiter of the engine. A value between 0 and 1. Setting this
attribute may have no effect, for example the thrust limit for a solid
rocket booster cannot be changed in flight.
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_Thrusters.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The components of the engine that generate thrust.
</summary>
  <remarks>
For example, this corresponds to the rocket nozzel on a solid rocket booster,
or the individual nozzels on a RAPIER engine.
The overall thrust produced by the engine, as reported by <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Engine.AvailableThrust" />,
<see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Engine.MaxThrust" /> and others, is the sum of the thrust generated by each thruster.
</remarks>
</doc>

Engine_get_SpecificImpulse.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The current specific impulse of the engine, in seconds. Returns zero
if the engine is not active.
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_VacuumSpecificImpulse.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The vacuum specific impulse of the engine, in seconds.
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_KerbinSeaLevelSpecificImpulse.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The specific impulse of the engine at sea level on Kerbin, in seconds.
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_PropellantNames.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The names of the propellants that the engine consumes.
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_Propellants.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The propellants that the engine consumes.
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_PropellantRatios.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The ratio of resources that the engine consumes. A dictionary mapping resource names
to the ratio at which they are consumed by the engine.
</summary>
  <remarks>
For example, if the ratios are 0.6 for LiquidFuel and 0.4 for Oxidizer, then for every 0.6 units of
LiquidFuel that the engine burns, it will burn 0.4 units of Oxidizer.
</remarks>
</doc>

Engine_get_HasFuel.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Whether the engine has any fuel available.
</summary>
  <remarks>
The engine must be activated for this property to update correctly.
</remarks>
</doc>

Engine_get_Throttle.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The current throttle setting for the engine. A value between 0 and 1.
This is not necessarily the same as the vessel's main throttle
setting, as some engines take time to adjust their throttle
(such as jet engines).
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_ThrottleLocked.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Whether the <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Control.Throttle" /> affects the engine. For example,
this is <c>true</c> for liquid fueled rockets, and <c>false</c> for solid rocket
boosters.
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_CanRestart.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Whether the engine can be restarted once shutdown. If the engine cannot be shutdown,
returns <c>false</c>. For example, this is <c>true</c> for liquid fueled rockets
and <c>false</c> for solid rocket boosters.
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_CanShutdown.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Whether the engine can be shutdown once activated. For example, this is
<c>true</c> for liquid fueled rockets and <c>false</c> for solid rocket boosters.
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_HasModes.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Whether the engine has multiple modes of operation.
</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_Mode.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>

</summary>

Engine_set_Mode.documentation:

</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_Modes.documentation:

Engine_get_AutoModeSwitch.documentation:

Engine_set_AutoModeSwitch.documentation:

Engine_set_GimbalLocked.documentation:

Engine_get_GimbalLimit.documentation:

Engine_set_GimbalLimit.documentation:

</summary>
</doc>

Engine_get_AvailableTorque.documentation:

A positive value means the part is gaining heat energy, and negative means it is losing heat energy.
</summary>
</doc>

Part_get_ThermalConductionFlux.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The rate at which heat energy is conducting into or out of the part via contact with other parts.
Measured in energy per unit time, or power, in Watts.
A positive value means the part is gaining heat energy, and negative means it is losing heat energy.
</summary>
</doc>

<doc>
  <summary>

A positive value means the part is gaining heat energy, and negative means it is losing heat energy.
</summary>
</doc>

<doc>

</summary>
</doc>

<doc>

and negative means its skin is gaining heat energy.

Vessel_get_ReferenceFrame.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The reference frame that is fixed relative to the vessel, and orientated with the vessel.
<list type="bullet"><item><description>The origin is at the center of mass of the vessel.</description></item><item><description>The axes rotate with the vessel.</description></item><item><description>The x-axis points out to the right of the vessel.</description></item><item><description>The y-axis points in the forward direction of the vessel.</description></item><item><description>The z-axis points out of the bottom off the vessel.</description></item></list></summary>
</doc>

Vessel_get_OrbitalReferenceFrame.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The reference frame that is fixed relative to the vessel, and orientated with the vessels
orbital prograde/normal/radial directions.
<list type="bullet"><item><description>The origin is at the center of mass of the vessel.</description></item><item><description>The axes rotate with the orbital prograde/normal/radial directions.</description></item><item><description>The x-axis points in the orbital anti-radial direction.</description></item><item><description>The y-axis points in the orbital prograde direction.</description></item><item><description>The z-axis points in the orbital normal direction.</description></item></list></summary>
  <remarks>
Be careful not to confuse this with 'orbit' mode on the navball.
</remarks>
</doc>

Vessel_get_SurfaceReferenceFrame.documentation: The reference frame that is fixed relative to the vessel, and orientated with the surface of the body being orbited. The origin is at the center of mass of the vessel.The axes rotate with the north and up directions on the surface of the body.The x-axis points in the zenith direction (upwards, normal to the body being orbited, from the center of the body towards the center of mass of the vessel).The y-axis points northwards towards the astronomical horizon (north, and tangential to the surface of the body -- the direction in which a compass would point when on the surface).The z-axis points eastwards towards the astronomical horizon (east, and tangential to the surface of the body -- east on a compass when on the surface). Be careful not to confuse this with 'surface' mode on the navball.

Vessel_get_SurfaceVelocityReferenceFrame.documentation: The reference frame that is fixed relative to the vessel, and orientated with the velocity vector of the vessel relative to the surface of the body being orbited. The origin is at the center of mass of the vessel.The axes rotate with the vessel's velocity vector.The y-axis points in the direction of the vessel's velocity vector, relative to the surface of the body being orbited.The z-axis is in the plane of the astronomical horizon.The x-axis is orthogonal to the other two axes.

</summary>
</doc>

Waypoint_get_MeanAltitude.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The altitude of the waypoint above sea level, in meters.
</summary>
</doc>

Waypoint_set_MeanAltitude.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The altitude of the waypoint above sea level, in meters.
</summary>
</doc>

Waypoint_get_SurfaceAltitude.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The altitude of the waypoint above the surface of the body or sea level, whichever is closer, in meters.
</summary>
</doc>

Waypoint_set_SurfaceAltitude.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The altitude of the waypoint above the surface of the body or sea level, whichever is closer, in meters.
</summary>
</doc>

Waypoint_get_BedrockAltitude.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The altitude of the waypoint above the surface of the body, in meters. When over water, this is the altitude above the sea floor.
</summary>
</doc>

Waypoint_set_BedrockAltitude.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The altitude of the waypoint above the surface of the body, in meters. When over water, this is the altitude above the sea floor.
</summary>
</doc>

Waypoint_get_NearSurface.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
True if waypoint is a point near or on the body rather than high in orbit.
</summary>
</doc>

Waypoint_get_Grounded.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
True if waypoint is actually glued to the ground.
</summary>
</doc>

Waypoint_get_Index.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The integer index of this waypoint amongst its cluster of sibling waypoints. 
In other words, when you have a cluster of waypoints called "Somewhere Alpha", "Somewhere Beta", and "Somewhere Gamma", 
then the alpha site has index 0, the beta site has index 1 and the gamma site has index 2. 
When <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Waypoint.Clustered" /> is false, this value is zero but meaningless.
</summary>
</doc>

Waypoint_get_Clustered.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
True if this waypoint is part of a set of clustered waypoints with greek letter names appended (Alpha, Beta, Gamma, etc). 
If true, there is a one-to-one correspondence with the greek letter name and the <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Waypoint.Index" />.
</summary>
</doc>

Waypoint_get_HasContract.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Whether the waypoint belongs to a contract.
</summary>
</doc>

Waypoint_get_ContractId.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The id of the associated contract.
Returns 0 if the waypoint does not belong to a contract.
</summary>
</doc>

WaypointManager_AddWaypoint.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Creates a waypoint at the given position at ground level, and returns a
<see cref="T:SpaceCenter.Waypoint" /> object that can be used to modify it.
</summary>
  <param name="latitude">Latitude of the waypoint.</param>
  <param name="longitude">Longitude of the waypoint.</param>
  <param name="body">Celestial body the waypoint is attached to.</param>
  <param name="name">Name of the waypoint.</param>
  <returns></returns>
</doc>

WaypointManager_get_Waypoints.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
A list of all existing waypoints.
</summary>
</doc>

WaypointManager_get_Colors.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
An example map of known color - seed pairs. 
Any other integers may be used as seed.
</summary>
</doc>

AutoPilot.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Provides basic auto-piloting utilities for a vessel.
Created by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Vessel.AutoPilot" />.
</summary>
  <remarks>
If a client engages the auto-pilot and then closes its connection to the server,
the auto-pilot will be disengaged and its target reference frame, direction and roll reset to default.
</remarks>
</doc>

Camera.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Controls the game's camera.
Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Camera" />.
</summary>
</doc>

CelestialBody.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Represents a celestial body (such as a planet or moon).
See <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Bodies" />.
</summary>
</doc>

Control.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Used to manipulate the controls of a vessel. This includes adjusting the
throttle, enabling/disabling systems such as SAS and RCS, or altering the
direction in which the vessel is pointing.
Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Vessel.Control" />.
</summary>
  <remarks>
Control inputs (such as pitch, yaw and roll) are zeroed when all clients
that have set one or more of these inputs are no longer connected.
</remarks>
</doc>

Flight.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Used to get flight telemetry for a vessel, by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Vessel.Flight" />.
All of the information returned by this class is given in the reference frame
passed to that method.
Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Vessel.Flight" />.
</summary>
  <remarks>
To get orbital information, such as the apoapsis or inclination, see <see cref="T:SpaceCenter.Orbit" />.
</remarks>
</doc>

Node.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Represents a maneuver node. Can be created using <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Control.AddNode" />.
</summary>
</doc>

Orbit.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Describes an orbit. For example, the orbit of a vessel, obtained by calling
<see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Vessel.Orbit" />, or a celestial body, obtained by calling
<see cref="M:SpaceCenter.CelestialBody.Orbit" />.
</summary>
</doc>

CargoBay.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
A cargo bay. Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.CargoBay" />.
</summary>
</doc>

ControlSurface.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
An aerodynamic control surface. Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.ControlSurface" />.
</summary>
</doc>

Decoupler.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
A decoupler. Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.Decoupler" /></summary>
</doc>

DockingPort.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
A docking port. Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.DockingPort" /></summary>
</doc>

Engine.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
An engine, including ones of various types.
For example liquid fuelled gimballed engines, solid rocket boosters and jet engines.
Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.Engine" />.
</summary>
  <remarks>
For RCS thrusters <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.RCS" />.
</remarks>
</doc>

Fairing.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
A fairing. Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.Fairing" />.
</summary>
</doc>

Intake.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
An air intake. Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.Intake" />.
</summary>
</doc>

LandingGear.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Landing gear with wheels. Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.LandingGear" />.
</summary>
</doc>

LandingLeg.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
A landing leg. Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.LandingLeg" />.
</summary>
</doc>

LaunchClamp.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
A launch clamp. Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.LaunchClamp" />.
</summary>
</doc>

Light.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
A light. Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.Light" />.
</summary>
</doc>

Module.documentation: This can be used to interact with a specific part module. This includes part modules in stock KSP, and those added by mods. In KSP, each part has zero or more PartModules associated with it. Each one contains some of the functionality of the part. For example, an engine has a "ModuleEngines" part module that contains all the functionality of an engine.

Parachute.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
A parachute. Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.Parachute" />.
</summary>
</doc>

Part.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Represents an individual part. Vessels are made up of multiple parts.
Instances of this class can be obtained by several methods in <see cref="T:SpaceCenter.Parts" />.
</summary>
</doc>

Parts.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Instances of this class are used to interact with the parts of a vessel.
An instance can be obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Vessel.Parts" />.
</summary>
</doc>

Propellant.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
A propellant for an engine. Obtains by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Engine.Propellants" />.
</summary>
</doc>

RCS.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
An RCS block or thruster. Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.RCS" />.
</summary>
</doc>

Radiator.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
A radiator. Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.Radiator" />.
</summary>
</doc>

ReactionWheel.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
A reaction wheel. Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.ReactionWheel" />.
</summary>
</doc>

ResourceConverter.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
A resource converter. Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.ResourceConverter" />.
</summary>
</doc>

ResourceHarvester.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
A resource harvester (drill). Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.ResourceHarvester" />.
</summary>
</doc>

Sensor.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
A sensor, such as a thermometer. Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.Sensor" />.
</summary>
</doc>

SolarPanel.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
A solar panel. Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.SolarPanel" />.
</summary>
</doc>

Thruster.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The component of an <see cref="T:SpaceCenter.Engine" /> or <see cref="T:SpaceCenter.RCS" /> part that generates thrust.
Can obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Engine.Thrusters" /> or <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.RCS.Thrusters" />.
</summary>
  <remarks>
Engines can consist of multiple thrusters.
For example, the S3 KS-25x4 "Mammoth" has four rocket nozzels, and so consists of four thrusters.
</remarks>
</doc>

ReferenceFrame.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Represents a reference frame for positions, rotations and
velocities. Contains:
<list type="bullet"><item><description>The position of the origin.</description></item><item><description>The directions of the x, y and z axes.</description></item><item><description>The linear velocity of the frame.</description></item><item><description>The angular velocity of the frame.</description></item></list></summary>
  <remarks>
This class does not contain any properties or methods. It is only
used as a parameter to other functions.
</remarks>
</doc>

Resource.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
An individual resource stored within a part.
Created using methods in the <see cref="T:SpaceCenter.Resources" /> class.
</summary>
</doc>

Resources.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Represents the collection of resources stored in a vessel, stage or part.
Created by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Vessel.Resources" />,
<see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Vessel.ResourcesInDecoupleStage" /> or
<see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Part.Resources" />.
</summary>
</doc>

Vessel.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
These objects are used to interact with vessels in KSP. This includes getting
orbital and flight data, manipulating control inputs and managing resources.
Created using <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.ActiveVessel" /> or <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Vessels" />.
</summary>
</doc>

Waypoint.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Represents a waypoint. Can be created using <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.WaypointManager.AddWaypoint" />.
</summary>
</doc>

WaypointManager.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Waypoints are the location markers you can see on the map view showing you where contracts are targeted for. 
With this structure, you can obtain coordinate data for the locations of these waypoints.
Obtained by calling <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.WaypointManager" />.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Automatic
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The camera is showing the active vessel, in "auto" mode.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Free
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The camera is showing the active vessel, in "free" mode.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Chase
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The camera is showing the active vessel, in "chase" mode.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Locked
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The camera is showing the active vessel, in "locked" mode.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Orbital
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The camera is showing the active vessel, in "orbital" mode.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: IVA
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The Intra-Vehicular Activity view is being shown.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Map
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The map view is being shown.
</summary>
</doc>

CargoBayState.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The state of a cargo bay. See <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.CargoBay.State" />.
</summary>
</doc>

DockingPortState.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The state of a docking port. See <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.DockingPort.State" />.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Ready
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The docking port is ready to dock to another docking port.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Docked
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The docking port is docked to another docking port, or docked to
another part (from the VAB/SPH).
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Docking
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The docking port is very close to another docking port,
but has not docked. It is using magnetic force to acquire a solid dock.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Undocking
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The docking port has just been undocked from another docking port,
and is disabled until it moves away by a sufficient distance
(<see cref="M:SpaceCenter.DockingPort.ReengageDistance" />).
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Shielded
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The docking port has a shield, and the shield is closed.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Moving
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The docking ports shield is currently opening/closing.
</summary>
</doc>

LandingGearState.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The state of a landing gear. See <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.LandingGear.State" />.
</summary>
</doc>

LandingLegState.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The state of a landing leg. See <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.LandingLeg.State" />.
</summary>
</doc>

ParachuteState.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The state of a parachute. See <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Parachute.State" />.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Active
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The parachute is still stowed, but ready to semi-deploy.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: SemiDeployed
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The parachute has been deployed and is providing some drag,
but is not fully deployed yet.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Stowed
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The parachute is safely tucked away inside its housing.
</summary>
</doc>

RadiatorState.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The state of a radiator. <see cref="T:SpaceCenter.RadiatorState" /></summary>
</doc>

ResourceConverterState.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The state of a resource converter. See <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.ResourceConverter.State" />.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: MissingResource
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Converter is missing a required resource.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: StorageFull
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
No available storage for output resource.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Unknown
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Unknown state. Possible with modified resource converters.
In this case, check <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.ResourceConverter.StatusInfo" /> for more information.
</summary>
</doc>

ResourceHarvesterState.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The state of a resource harvester. See <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.ResourceHarvester.State" />.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Deployed
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The drill is deployed and ready.
</summary>
</doc>

SolarPanelState.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The state of a solar panel. See <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.SolarPanel.State" />.
</summary>
</doc>

ResourceFlowMode.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The way in which a resource flows between parts. See <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Resources.FlowMode" />.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Vessel
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The resource flows to any part in the vessel. For example, electric charge.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Stage
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The resource flows from parts in the first stage, followed by the second,
and so on. For example, mono-propellant.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Adjacent
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The resource flows between adjacent parts within the vessel. For example,
liquid fuel or oxidizer.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: None
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The resource does not flow. For example, solid fuel.
</summary>
</doc>

SASMode.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The behavior of the SAS auto-pilot. See <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.AutoPilot.SASMode" />.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: StabilityAssist
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Stability assist mode. Dampen out any rotation.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Maneuver
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Point in the burn direction of the next maneuver node.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Normal
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Point in the orbit normal direction.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: AntiNormal
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Point in the orbit anti-normal direction.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Radial
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Point in the orbit radial direction.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: AntiRadial
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Point in the orbit anti-radial direction.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Target
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Point in the direction of the current target.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: AntiTarget
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Point away from the current target.
</summary>
</doc>

SpeedMode.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The mode of the speed reported in the navball.
See <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Control.SpeedMode" />.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Orbit
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Speed is relative to the vessel's orbit.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Surface
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Speed is relative to the surface of the body being orbited.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Target
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Speed is relative to the current target.
</summary>
</doc>

VesselSituation.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The situation a vessel is in.

</summary>
</doc>

values.name: SubOrbital
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Vessel is on a sub-orbital trajectory.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Flying
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Vessel is flying through an atmosphere.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Landed
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Vessel is landed on the surface of a body.
</summary>
</doc>

values.name: Splashed
values.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
Vessel has splashed down in an ocean.
</summary>
</doc>

VesselType.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The type of a vessel.
See <see cref="M:SpaceCenter.Vessel.Type" />.
</summary>
</doc>

WarpMode.documentation:
<doc>
  <summary>
The time warp mode.
Returned by <see cref="T:SpaceCenter.WarpMode" /></summary>
</doc>

values.name: Rails

<doc>
  <summary>
Time warp is active, and in regular "on-rails" mode.

Time warp is active, and in physical time warp mode.
